text:
Fifth Avenue, north across 35th Street, showing an early view of this arterial thoroughfare at the start of its transition from a residential nature to a business street. In the center is the then dominant Brick Presbyterian Church at the N. W. corner of 37th Street. The spires in the distance are atop the Church of the Divine Paternity (45th St.) and the Collegiate Reformed Protestant Dutch Church (48th St.).
About 1890

title: 364 Fifth Avenue - West 35th Street

text:
Fifth Avenue, west side, south from 35th Street, showing from left to right, the Caswell home (became the University Club and which was remodelled in the Queen Anne style in 1887 for the New York Club), the A. T. Stewart home (became the Manhattan Club in 1891), the twin Astor homes (removed separately for the Waldorf (in 1893) Astoria (about 1897) Hotel), and the then dominant Marble Collegiate Church (erected 1851-4). Absent in this view are two items that appear in slightly later photos. These are the Fifth Avenue Art Galleries, a two story structure, erected by the Caswell estate between their home and the Stewart house, and the Hotel Cambridge at the S. W. corner of 33rd Street.

About 1876
